  footnotes: []
english:
  title: An Ancient Poem
  author: Yoo In-chum
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Mount Zhongnan glows blue-green at dawn,
    Distant, the layered city towers rise.
    From my north window, a tender dream disperses—
    After rain, the world grows cool upon my soul.

    Sitting alone here, how deep the stillness,
    Yet noble birds answer with their song.
    I plant bamboo and chrysanthemums at whim,
    Matching the longing that dwells within my heart:
    To transcend this world, to slip its grasp.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Mount Zhongnan (終南山) is a sacred mountain south of Chang'an (modern-day Xi'an), traditionally associated with hermitage and spiritual retreat in Chinese poetry.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'north window' suggests a scholar's study, a traditional setting for contemplation in East Asian poetry.
  - key: ''
    value: Bamboo and chrysanthemum are classical symbols of virtue and noble character in Chinese and East Asian literary tradition.
